text: I saw the movie yesterday. It has some amazing performances. In particular, Jennifer Jason Leigh gives a riveting performance as a murdering gang member named Daisy Domergue, who has been apprehended by a bounty hunter (played by Kurt Russell) who is transporting her to prison to be executed. This movie is over three hours long but the suspense and action keep you entertained throughout. The movie is filled with a lot of violence and profanity. It's an "equal opportunity offender"- it contains enough controversial material to offend everyone. The offensive material contained in the movie includes: violence against women; racism towards African Americans; racism towards Mexicans; violence against the elderly; sodomy; and excessive use of force by law enforcement officials. It also tackles some positive things like the camaraderie that develops between people from different backgrounds, when faced with a common threat/ enemy. #TheHatefulEight #QuentinTarantino

text: I perused through a couple of reviews of Tarantino's latest movie, "The Hateful Eight." I have not seen any of his work since "Pulp Fiction," because principally and morally I believe revenge in the hands of man is reprehensible and offers NO restitution, NO closure of any kind. And, the theme of revenge and its merits are what "Kill Bill" and the rest of his films that followed appear to forward.  I can't deny that Quentin is masterful at his trade..."Pulp Fiction" was cinematic excellence, bar none. But, I tend to shy away from Hollywood Directors who say they want to conjure up every imaginable manner of KILLING someone, then show you in gruesome detail how that's done. And, the film's message is typically the same: if someone hurts you, hurt them right back... and make sure to murder them in front of their 5-year old child while you're at it.  Sorry, but that's just not my idea of entertainment. Life offers enough pain and suffering. Why would I want to pay $14 to incur two more hours of it? If you see his latest film and disagree with me, I'm all ears. Outside of that, I believe the man needs psychiatric help.
